You don&#39;t aggregate correctly the table orderlines.&lt;br/&gt;
You compare the sums without returning them from the query.&lt;br/&gt;
Try this:

    select o.orderid
    from orders o inner join (
      select orderid, sum(sales) sumsales, sum(units) sumunits
      from orderlines
      group by orderid 
    ) s on s.orderid = o.orderid
    where s.sumsales &lt;&gt; o.sales or s.sumunits &lt;&gt; o.units

A single class or interface can&#39;t extend or implement a union of things, so it isn&#39;t possible to achieve what you want directly.  If you really need a single class to give you behavior like a discriminated union, I would think about using a [generic](https://www.typescriptlang.org/docs/handbook/generics.html) class in which your dependent property is of a [conditional type](https://github.com/Microsoft/TypeScript/wiki/What&#39;s-new-in-TypeScript#conditional-types):

    class Example&lt;T extends C[&quot;thing&quot;]&gt; {
      constructor(
        public thing: T,
        public otherThing: Extract&lt;C, { thing: T }&gt;[&quot;otherThing&quot;]
      ) {}
    }

In the specific instance where the discriminant property `thing` is a valid key type (and `1 | 2` works), you can use [mapped types](https://www.typescriptlang.org/docs/handbook/advanced-types.html#mapped-types) instead of conditional types (although I&#39;ll make the mapping out of a conditional type like this):

    type MappedOtherThing = {
      [K in C[&quot;thing&quot;]]: Extract&lt;C, { thing: K }&gt;[&quot;otherThing&quot;]
    };
    
    class Example&lt;T extends C[&quot;thing&quot;]&gt; {
      constructor(public thing: T, public otherThing: MappedOtherThing[T]) {}
    }


The `Extract&lt;C, {thing: T}&gt;[&quot;otherThing&quot;]` uses the [`Extract`](https://www.typescriptlang.org/docs/handbook/utility-types.html#extracttu) utility type to find the member of `C` which is assignable to `{thing: T}`, and then [looks up](https://github.com/Microsoft/TypeScript/wiki/What&#39;s-new-in-TypeScript#keyof-and-lookup-types) its `otherThing` property.

Either of those implementations will give you this behavior:

    const eA = new Example(1, &quot;okay&quot;); // Example&lt;1&gt;
    eA.otherThing; // string
    const a: A = eA; // okay
    const eB = new Example(2, 12345); // Example&lt;2&gt;
    eB.otherThing; // number
    const b: B = eB; // okay
    const c: C = Math.random() &lt; 0.5 ? eA : eB; // okay


Hope that helps.  Good luck!

